  footnotes: []
english:
  title: To the Tune of the Silver Lamp
  author: Choe Jip-gyun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last night I read the Records of Three Kingdoms with care,
    Laughing at Cao Cao, Sun Quan, Liu Bei.
    They exhausted every stratagem, spent all their wit,
    Only to carve the realm into thirds.

    Pondering it well, I ask:
    How different is it from Liu Ling's single drunken spell?
    Humans do not see a hundred years,
    Childhood passes in ignorance, age brings weakness and disease—
    Only this brief middle span of youth remains,
    Yet we bind ourselves with hollow fame.
    Though one climbs to the highest rank, ten thousand bushels of grain fill the store,
    Tell me, how can white hair ever be escaped?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Records of Three Kingdoms (蜀志) refers to the period of disunion in Chinese history when three rival states competed for dominance, each ruler employing cunning and force to secure power.
  - key: ''
    value: Liu Ling (劉伶) was one of the Seven Sages of the Bamboo Grove, a Daoist philosopher known for his love of wine and freedom from worldly concerns. His single drunken moment suggests a transcendence beyond the machinations of power.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The poem reflects a Daoist and Buddhist critique of ambition: despite achieving the highest offices and greatest wealth, no one can escape the inevitable decline and mortality that comes with age.'
